Karan
Both "make it and eat" and "make it and have" are grammatically correct, but the choice depends on the context and personal preference.

"Make it and eat" is a straightforward and commonly used phrase, especially when referring to food. It simply means to prepare the dish and then consume it.

"Make it and have" is also correct and can be used interchangeably with "make it and eat." In some contexts, "have" might sound slightly more formal or polite, but both convey the same meaning.

Ultimately, you can use either phrase depending on what feels more natural to you or the tone you want to convey. Both convey the idea of preparing and enjoying the white sauce pasta.
